3. Three learnings from Part A:

 HTML 
- Buttons should explicitly use type="button" because the default type inside forms is submit, which can cause unintended behavior later.

b) CSS

- Font-family names should use their standard capitalization (e.g., Merriweather, Inter) for clarity and consistency.
- Choosing the correct fallback font is important; 
since Merriweather is a serif font, the appropriate fallback is serif, not sans-serif.
- Page layout should not rely only on browser defaults; 
explicitly setting spacing (e.g., margin and padding) improves layout control and consistency.

Part B: Ethics and Risks

3 ethical issues and mitigations: 

1. Security vulnerabilities
Ai-generated code as well human-written code are not flawless and can contain security flaws. 
There can be errors leading to XXS, SQL or other input-related vulnerabilities.
If developers rely on AI-generated code without reviewing it carefully, 
these weaknesses could be introduced into an application and potentially exploited by attackers.

To reduce this risk, I will treat AI-generated code as a code draft that needs always be reviewed and tested. 
I will check the code for security issues, sanitize user inputs.

2. Confidential code and data
The data used by AI tend to leak and become available to other ones. It happened if proprietary code, 
API keys, or customer information are pasted into an AI system.

To prevent this, I will avoid sharing any sensitive or PII with AI tools.
When asking for help, I will replace real data with dummy data, 
so no confidential information is exposed while still allowing me to use AI for assistance. 

3. Accuracy and hallucinations
AI systems tends to sometimes generate incorrect or misleading information. 
It could be code snippets, explanations, bug fixing, etc. 
To address this risk, I will verify AI-generated information by checking official documentation, 
trusted  resources, and testing the code myself. 